Certainly! Below is a basic example of a C++ program that accomplishes the task you've described. This program will prompt the user for the name of the text file to read and the specific word to count within that file. It then opens the file, reads it line by line, and counts the number of times the specified word appears.

Please note that this example assumes the word boundaries are defined by spaces and punctuation marks, and it does not consider word variations (like plural forms or different tenses) as matches. This example is also case-sensitive.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <sstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    string filename, word, line;
    int count = 0;

    // Ask for the file name
    cout << "Enter the filename to read: ";
    cin >> filename;

    // Ask for the word to count
    cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    cin >> word;

    // Open the file
    ifstream file(filename);

    if (!file.is_open()) {
        cerr << "Could not open the file - '" << filename << "'" << endl;
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    // Read the file line by line
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        // Use a stringstream to break the line into words
        stringstream ss(line);
        string currentWord;

        // Check each word
        while (ss >> currentWord) {
            if (currentWord == word) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    }

    // Close the file
    file.close();

    // Output the result
    cout << "The word '" << word << "' appears " << count << " times in the file." << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Before running this program, ensure you have a text file to read from, and you know its path. When you compile and run this program, it will ask for the filename (you need to provide the path if the file is not in the same directory as the executable) and the word you're interested in counting. After processing, it will display the count of how many times that word appears in the text file.

This program does not handle all edge cases, such as different capitalizations of the word (Word vs word), words followed by punctuation (word, word.), or other variations. For more advanced use cases, you might need to implement additional string processing logic.
